In [189]:
def plot_dendrogram(model, **kwargs):
    # create the counts of samples under each node
    counts = np.zeros(model.children_.shape[0])
    n_samples = len(model.labels_)
    for i, merge in enumerate(model.children_):
        current_count = 0
        for child_idx in merge:
            if child_idx < n_samples:
                current_count += 1  # leaf node
            else:
                current_count += counts[child_idx - n_samples]
        counts[i] = current_count

    linkage_matrix = np.column_stack([model.children_, model.distances_,
                                      counts]).astype(float)

    # Plot the corresponding dendrogram
    dendrogram(linkage_matrix, **kwargs)

plt.figure(figsize=(13,14))
plt.title('Hierarchical Clustering Dendrogram')
# plot the top three levels of the dendrogram
plot_dendrogram(agglom, truncate_mode='level', p=3)
plt.show()

Based on the dendogram we see that with threshold at 120 we can get 6 clusters and with little larger threshold, we can get only 4. That means we can't get the exact amount of rush hours using threshold for our cluster model.

There's a quite a lot of difference between the two pair plots. In the first one, with the valid target data, most of the delays happen with number of train stops at around 10. Also, most delays happen in the morning and between rush hours. In the second plot with the clustered data, we see very little amount of train departures with delays for each rush hour. Also it seems like trains with stops between 2 and 6 have delays and with stops from 8 and more there are no delays at all.

Let's validate our results.

# Define labels for species
actual = df2['DelayOrNot'].unique()

# Define labels for clusters
clusters = df2['Clustered DelayOrNot'].unique()

# Sort cluster names in alphabetical order, i.e.,
# Cluster 0, Cluster 1, Cluster 2, etc.
clusters.sort()

# Determine the location for cluster labels 
x_c = np.arange(len(clusters))

# Define the width of the bars
width = 0.25

# Create the bar plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16,10))
offset = -width
for spec in actual:
    nr_occurrences = []
    for clus in clusters:
        nr = df2[(df2['Clustered DelayOrNot']==clus) & (df2['DelayOrNot'] == spec)]['Clustered DelayOrNot'].count()
        nr_occurrences.append(nr)
    rects = ax.bar(x_c + offset, nr_occurrences, width, label=spec)
    offset = offset + width

# Add text for labels, title and custom x-axis tick labels, etc.
ax.set_ylabel('Number of occurrences')
ax.set_title('Number of occurrences in cluster')
ax.set_xticks(x_c)
ax.set_xticklabels(clusters)
ax.legend()

fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Based on the plot we can see the two clusters and how the actual data was distributed between them. The 0 (blue bar) shows no delay and 1 (orange bar) shows delay. In the first cluster 0, we see that most of the train departures had no delay with count of above 17000, but there were also departures with delays that were almost the same amount. The results in the second cluster are the same, with the difference that the amount is much less with around 5000. But again the delay and no delay departures are mixed and it is not clear if this cluster holds only delays or no delays.

Conclusion¶

The cluster model is useful when we use it to predict the rush hours, based on the features we have. We found quite different rush hours using Agglomerative Clustering that fit better with the data, compared with the rush hours we identified.

About predicting if there is delay or not, the algorithm did not perform well and we can not say which cluster holds delays or no delays.
